</FONT></P>

<!-- TOC_END -->
<P ALIGN="CENTER" style="font-family:times;"><FONT SIZE=2><A
NAME="dy43801_item_four_#151;advisor__dy402162"> </A>
<A NAME="toc_dy43801_1"> </A>
<BR></FONT><FONT SIZE=2><B>  ITEM FOUR&#151;ADVISORY APROVAL OF EXECUTIVE COMPENSATION    <BR>    </B></FONT></P>

<P style="font-family:times;text-align:justify"><FONT SIZE=2>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;Consistent with the views expressed by shareholders at our 2011 Annual Meeting, the Board of Directors has determined to seek an annual
non-binding advisory vote from shareholders to approve the executive compensation as disclosed in the Compensation Discussion&nbsp;&amp; Analysis ("CD&amp;A"), tabular disclosures and related
narrative of this proxy statement. </FONT></P>

<P style="font-family:times;text-align:justify"><FONT SIZE=2>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;Target's
executive compensation programs are structured to align the interests of our executive officers with the interests of our shareholders. They are designed to attract, retain, and
motivate a premier management team to sustain our distinctive brand and competitive advantage in the marketplace and to provide a framework that delivers outstanding financial results over the long
term. Our executive compensation programs reflect the competitive environment in which we operate, and incorporate performance based criteria. More specifically,
we:</FONT></P>

<UL>
<DL compact>
<DT style='font-family:times;margin-bottom:-11pt;'><FONT SIZE=2>&#149;</FONT></DT><DD style="font-family:times;text-align:justify"><FONT SIZE=2>Incorporate a mix of cash and equity compensation with varying time horizons and financial measures to reward sustained
outstanding performance; </FONT><FONT SIZE=2>
<BR><BR></FONT></DD><DT style='font-family:times;margin-bottom:-11pt;'><FONT SIZE=2>&#149;</FONT></DT><DD style="font-family:times;text-align:justify"><FONT SIZE=2>Put an emphasis on variable compensation with financial performance measures that correlate with the creation of
shareholder value; and </FONT><FONT SIZE=2>
<BR><BR></FONT></DD><DT style='font-family:times;margin-bottom:-11pt;'><FONT SIZE=2>&#149;</FONT></DT><DD style="font-family:times;text-align:justify"><FONT SIZE=2>Directly align the interests of our executive officers with those of our shareholders by linking long-term
compensation to stock price performance. </FONT></DD></DL>
</UL>

<P style="font-family:times;text-align:justify"><FONT SIZE=2>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;Shareholders
are urged to read the CD&amp;A, which discusses in-depth how our executive compensation programs are aligned with our performance and the creation of shareholder
value. The Compensation Committee and the Board of Directors believe that the policies and practices described in the CD&amp;A effectively implement our pay for performance compensation philosophy. </FONT></P>

<P style="font-family:times;text-align:justify"><FONT SIZE=2>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;</FONT><FONT
SIZE=2><B>THE BOARD OF DIRECTORS, UPON RECOMMENDATION OF THE COMPENSATION COMMITTEE, RECOMMENDS THAT SHAREHOLDERS VOTE "FOR" APPROVAL OF THE FOLLOWING
NON-BINDING RESOLUTION:  </B></FONT></P>

<P style="font-family:times;text-align:justify"><FONT SIZE=2>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;</FONT><FONT SIZE=2><B>"RESOLVED, that the shareholders approve the compensation awarded to the named executive officers, as described in the CD&amp;A, tabular
disclosures, and other narrative executive compensation disclosures in this proxy statement."  </B></FONT></P>

<P style="font-family:times;text-align:justify"><FONT SIZE=2><B> Effect of Item  </B></FONT></P>

<P style="font-family:times;text-align:justify"><FONT SIZE=2>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;The Say-on-Pay resolution is non-binding. The approval or disapproval of this item by shareholders
will not require the Board or the Compensation Committee to take any action regarding Target's executive compensation practices. The final decision on the compensation and benefits of our executive
officers and on whether, and if so, how, to address shareholder disapproval remains with the Board and the Compensation Committee. </FONT></P>


<P style="font-family:times;text-align:justify"><FONT SIZE=2>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;The
Board believes that the Compensation Committee is in the best position to consider the extensive information and factors necessary to make independent, objective, and competitive
compensation recommendations and decisions that are in the best interest of Target and its shareholders. </FONT></P>

<P style="font-family:times;text-align:justify"><FONT SIZE=2>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;The
Board values the opinions of Target's shareholders as expressed through their votes and other communications. Although the resolution is non-binding, the Board will
carefully consider the outcome of the advisory vote on executive compensation and shareholder opinions received from other communications when making future compensation decisions. </FONT></P>

<P ALIGN="CENTER" style="font-family:times;"><FONT SIZE=2>55</FONT></P>

<HR NOSHADE>
<P style='font-family:times;page-break-before:always'></p>
<!-- ZEQ.=1,SEQ=61,EFW="2207783",CP="TARGET CORPORATION",DN="1",CHK=822707,FOLIO='55',FILE='DISK114:[12ZAC1.12ZAC43801]DY43801A.;14',USER='DBEMBEN',CD='27-APR-2012;04:12' -->
<A NAME="page_dy43801_1_56"> </A>
<P ALIGN="CENTER" style="font-family:times;"><FONT SIZE=2><A
NAME="dy43801_item_five_#151;shareho__dy402233"> </A>
<A NAME="toc_dy43801_2"> </A>
<BR></FONT><FONT SIZE=2><B>  ITEM FIVE&#151;SHAREHOLDER PROPOSAL ON ELECTRONICS RECYCLING    <BR>    </B></FONT></P>

<P style="font-family:times;text-align:justify"><FONT SIZE=2>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;As You Sow, 311 California Street, Suite&nbsp;510, San Francisco, CA 94104, on behalf of shareholder Margaret Law, who held more than
$2,000 of shares of common stock on December&nbsp;30, 2011, intends to submit the following resolution to shareholders for approval at the 2012 annual meeting: </FONT></P>

<P ALIGN="CENTER" style="font-family:times;"><FONT SIZE=2><A
NAME="dy43801_resolution"> </A>
<A NAME="toc_dy43801_3"> </A>
<BR></FONT><FONT SIZE=2><B>  Resolution    <BR>    </B></FONT></P>

<P style="font-family:times;text-align:justify"><FONT SIZE=2>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;RESOLVED that Target Corp.'s board of directors prepare a report, at reasonable cost and excluding confidential information, on policy
options, above and beyond legal compliance, to minimize the environmental impacts of its electronics recycling activities by providing mechanisms for take back of all electronics sold, promoting reuse
of working equipment and preventing export to non-OECD countries of hazardous e-waste and untested or non-working equipment or components. </FONT></P>

<P ALIGN="CENTER" style="font-family:times;"><FONT SIZE=2><A
NAME="dy43801_supporting_statement"> </A>
<A NAME="toc_dy43801_4"> </A>
<BR></FONT><FONT SIZE=2><B>  Supporting Statement    <BR>    </B></FONT></P>

<P style="font-family:times;text-align:justify"><FONT SIZE=2>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;WHEREAS Target Corp. is the fourth largest U.S. retailer of consumer electronics, and such devices contain toxic materials such as
lead, mercury, cadmium, brominated flame retardants, polyvinyl chloride, and are difficult to recycle. </FONT></P>

<P style="font-family:times;text-align:justify"><FONT SIZE=2>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;Only
about 25% of electronics ready for end-of-life management are collected for recycling, according to a 2011 U.S. Environmental Protection Agency report.
E-waste is the fastest growing and most hazardous component of the municipal waste stream, comprising more than 5%. The estimated collection rate for e-waste lags the U.S.
recovery rate for all municipal waste of 34%. </FONT></P>

<P style="font-family:times;text-align:justify"><FONT SIZE=2>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;Improper
disposal of electronics can result in serious public health and environmental impacts. Analog TV sets and monitors with cathode ray tubes contain large amounts of lead, flat
screen monitors contain mercury switches, and computer batteries contain cadmium, which can be harmful to human health if released to the environment. </FONT></P>


<P style="font-family:times;text-align:justify"><FONT SIZE=2>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;Electronic
goods collected for recycling in the U.S. are often shipped by recyclers to developing countries where they endanger health and the environment. </FONT> <FONT SIZE=2><I>Exporting Harm: The High-Tech Trashing of Asia</I></FONT><FONT SIZE=2>, a report
by Basel Action Network, revealed appalling conditions in the city of Guiyu, China,
where approximately 100,000 migrant workers break apart and process old electronic equipment under primitive conditions. Workers openly burn toxic plastics and wires, and melt soldered circuit boards
to extract gold, silver and copper. These activities threaten worker health and pollute land and water. </FONT></P>

<P style="font-family:times;text-align:justify"><FONT SIZE=2>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;Target's
2009 Corporate Responsibility report states "being a responsible steward of the environment is one of the most important issues that defines Target's corporate reputation," yet
the company does not offer take back for the full range of electronics it sells and lacks a policy to ensure safe disposal of materials collected. The company takes back small devices such as music
players and mobile phones but does not disclose substantive information about the disposition of electronics it collects, or whether it promotes reuse of working equipment or bars export of collected
electronics. Shareholders need assurances the company is actively monitoring how collected goods are processed. </FONT></P>

<P style="font-family:times;text-align:justify"><FONT SIZE=2>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;Proponents
believe our company should develop a nationwide return program for all electronic devices it sells using stores or nearby locations convenient for customers. All electronics
collected by our company should be recycled or refurbished by responsible electronics recyclers who are independently verified to meet a standard such as the e-Stewards standard.
Competitor Best Buy takes back all electronics and bars downstream service providers from exporting non-working equipment or components to developing countries, and requires third party
provider audits. </FONT></P>

<P style="font-family:times;text-align:justify"><FONT SIZE=2><B> Position of the Board of Directors  </B></FONT></P>

<P style="font-family:times;text-align:justify"><FONT SIZE=2>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;The Board of Directors has considered this proposal and believes that its adoption at this time is not in the best interests of Target
or our shareholders. In response to a similar proposal last year, we improved </FONT></P>

<P ALIGN="CENTER" style="font-family:times;"><FONT SIZE=2>56</FONT></P>

<HR NOSHADE>
<P style='font-family:times;page-break-before:always'></p>
<!-- ZEQ.=2,SEQ=62,EFW="2207783",CP="TARGET CORPORATION",DN="1",CHK=229969,FOLIO='56',FILE='DISK114:[12ZAC1.12ZAC43801]DY43801A.;14',USER='DBEMBEN',CD='27-APR-2012;04:12' -->
<A NAME="page_dy43801_1_57"> </A>

<P style="font-family:times;text-align:justify"><FONT SIZE=2>our
disclosure with respect to our electronics recycling activities. In particular, we now address in more detail our responsible recycling standards for e-waste, our in-store
recycling program, where our recycling products go and other efforts to divert waste from landfills at </FONT><FONT SIZE=2><I>hereforgood.target.com/environment</I></FONT><FONT SIZE=2>. Our
responsible recycling standards for e-waste, which we contractually obligate our vendor partners to follow, address several of the concerns mentioned by the proponent. Those standards
include:</FONT></P>

<UL>
<DL compact>
<DT style='font-family:times;margin-bottom:-11pt;'><FONT SIZE=2>&#149;</FONT></DT><DD style="font-family:times;text-align:justify"><FONT SIZE=2>Ensuring that all items are refurbished, broken down and recycled or marketed for re-use. </FONT> <FONT SIZE=2>
<BR><BR></FONT></DD><DT style='font-family:times;margin-bottom:-11pt;'><FONT SIZE=2>&#149;</FONT></DT><DD style="font-family:times;text-align:justify"><FONT SIZE=2>Processing all e-waste items domestically, and preventing e-waste materials from being sent to
landfills anywhere in the world. </FONT><FONT SIZE=2>
<BR><BR></FONT></DD><DT style='font-family:times;margin-bottom:-11pt;'><FONT SIZE=2>&#149;</FONT></DT><DD style="font-family:times;text-align:justify"><FONT SIZE=2>Monthly reporting by vendors on all sales and recycling activity, which, along with site audits, encourages transparency
and allows visibility into vendor processes. </FONT></DD></DL>
</UL>

<P style="font-family:times;text-align:justify"><FONT SIZE=2>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;Our
program includes consideration of whether vendors have met various certification standards (such as the e-Stewards standard mentioned in the proposal and the Responsible
Recycling (R2) standard), the vendors' internal processes and reputation, and periodic process reviews and inspections by appropriate Target team members or third-party inspectors. The vendor
responsible for the majority of Target's e-waste processing is independently certified to meet the R2 standard. </FONT></P>

<P style="font-family:times;text-align:justify"><FONT SIZE=2>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;The
proposal received this year differs from last year's proposal in that it asks us to consider expanding the scope of our guest-facing recycling program to include "all electronics
sold." Our guest-facing recycling program already allows guests to easily recycle small electronics, such as MP3 players, ink cartridges and cell phones, as well as cans, glass and plastic bottles and
plastic bags in their local Target store. In essence, the substance of the proposal is to ask us to cover larger electronics, such as televisions, game consoles and appliances, in our guest-facing
recycling program. We do not believe such an expansive recycling program is common among general merchandise retailers. In addition, we
believe that the nature of a more expanded program would be disruptive to our store operations and less efficient relative to other alternatives available to guests for disposal of such items,
including the availability of local government-run recycling facilities. </FONT></P>

<P style="font-family:times;text-align:justify"><FONT SIZE=2>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;We
do not believe a separate report is needed because we already actively monitor our recycling and disposal practices for e-waste above and beyond legal compliance, and our
existing recycling program, including our electronics take back, is consistent with, if not ahead of, practices among general merchandise retailers. Based on the above, the Board believes that our
current approach to e-waste is appropriate and is in the best interest of Target and our shareholders. </FONT></P>

<P style="font-family:times;text-align:justify"><FONT SIZE=2>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;</FONT><FONT
SIZE=2><B>THE BOARD OF DIRECTORS RECOMMENDS THAT SHAREHOLDERS VOTE "AGAINST" THE SHAREHOLDER PROPOSAL ON ELECTRONICS RECYCLING.  </B></FONT></P>

<P ALIGN="CENTER" style="font-family:times;"><FONT SIZE=2><B> <A NAME="dy43801_item_six_#151;shareholder_prop__ite04205"> </A>
<A NAME="toc_dy43801_5"> </A>
<BR>  ITEM SIX&#151;SHAREHOLDER PROPOSAL ON PROHIBITING USE<BR>  OF CORPORATE FUNDS FOR POLITICAL ELECTIONS OR CAMPAIGNS    <BR>    </B></FONT></P>


<P style="font-family:times;text-align:justify"><FONT SIZE=2>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;Green Century Equity Fund, 114 State Street, Suite&nbsp;200, Boston, MA 02109, which held more than $2,000 of shares of common stock
on December&nbsp;22, 2011, intends to submit the following resolution to shareholders for approval at the 2012 annual meeting: </FONT></P>

<P ALIGN="CENTER" style="font-family:times;"><FONT SIZE=2><A
NAME="dy43801_resolution_1"> </A>
<A NAME="toc_dy43801_6"> </A>
<BR></FONT><FONT SIZE=2><B>  Resolution    <BR>    </B></FONT></P>

<P style="font-family:times;text-align:justify"><FONT SIZE=2>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;RESOLVED: The shareholders request that the board of directors adopt a policy prohibiting the use of corporate funds for any political
election or campaign. </FONT></P>

<P ALIGN="CENTER" style="font-family:times;"><FONT SIZE=2>57</FONT></P>

<HR NOSHADE>
<P style='font-family:times;page-break-before:always'></p>
<!-- ZEQ.=3,SEQ=63,EFW="2207783",CP="TARGET CORPORATION",DN="1",CHK=334161,FOLIO='57',FILE='DISK114:[12ZAC1.12ZAC43801]DY43801A.;14',USER='DBEMBEN',CD='27-APR-2012;04:12' -->
<A NAME="page_dy43801_1_58"> </A>
<P ALIGN="CENTER" style="font-family:times;"><FONT SIZE=2><A
NAME="dy43801_supporting_statement_1"> </A>
<A NAME="toc_dy43801_7"> </A>
<BR></FONT><FONT SIZE=2><B>  Supporting Statement    <BR>    </B></FONT></P>

<P ALIGN="CENTER" style="font-family:times;"><FONT SIZE=2><A
NAME="dy43801_prohibit_political_spe__dy402449"> </A>
<A NAME="toc_dy43801_8"> </A></FONT> <FONT SIZE=2>PROHIBIT POLITICAL SPENDING FROM CORPORATE TREASURY FUNDS    <BR></FONT></P>

<P style="font-family:times;text-align:justify"><FONT SIZE=2>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;WHEREAS:
Political spending and corporate money in politics is a highly contentious issue, made more prominent in light of the 2010 </FONT> <FONT SIZE=2><I>Citizens United</I></FONT><FONT SIZE=2> Supreme Court case that affirmed companies' rights to make
unlimited political expenditures to independent groups. In the 2012 election
year, we expect even more media and public attention to corporate spending to influence elections. Experts predict that an unprecedented amount of money will be spent in the 2012 election season. </FONT></P>

<P style="font-family:times;text-align:justify"><FONT SIZE=2>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;Recent
polls highlight the public's disapproval. In a June 2010 Harris poll, 85% of voters said that corporations "have too much influence over the political system today...." In
February 2010, an ABC News/Washington Post poll found that 80% opposed </FONT><FONT SIZE=2><I>Citizens United</I></FONT><FONT SIZE=2>, noting, "the bipartisan nature of these views is striking in
these largely partisan times." </FONT></P>

<P style="font-family:times;text-align:justify"><FONT SIZE=2>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;Corporate
political contributions can backfire on a corporation's reputation and bottom line. In 2010, Target Corporation experienced such risks directly after it received unwanted
attention, consumer boycotts, and protests for its support of a controversial candidate. In a Harris Poll released in October 2010, a sizable portion (46)% of respondents indicated that if there were
option, they would shop elsewhere if they learned that a business they patronized had contributed to a candidate or a cause that they oppose. </FONT></P>


<P style="font-family:times;text-align:justify"><FONT SIZE=2>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;According
to the National Institute on Money in State Politics, between 2003 and 2011, Target Corporation spent $1.5&nbsp;million on company or PAC contributions. However, this figure
does not include payments to trade associations or other tax-exempt organizations that may channel corporate money to political ends. </FONT></P>

<P style="font-family:times;text-align:justify"><FONT SIZE=2>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;Many
trade associations that receive corporate contributions spend vast sums in electoral politics; these payments are not required to be disclosed. For example, the U.S. Chamber of
Commerce pledged to spend between $50 and $75&nbsp;million in the 2010 election season, and announced that it would work to unseat any member of Congress who voted for healthcare reform. According
to Public Citizen, only 32% of groups broadcasting electioneering communications in the 2010 primary season revealed the
identities of donors in their Federal Election Commission filings, down from nearly 100&nbsp;percent in the 2004 and 2006 cycles. </FONT></P>

<P style="font-family:times;text-align:justify"><FONT SIZE=2>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;Increasingly,
companies such as IBM, Colgate Palmolive, Wells Fargo and others are adopting policies prohibiting spending of political funds directly or indirectly to influence
elections. </FONT></P>

<P style="font-family:times;text-align:justify"><FONT SIZE=2>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;Given
the risks and potential negative impact on shareholder value, the proponents believe Target Corporation should adopt a policy to refrain from using treasury funds in the political
process. </FONT></P>

<P style="font-family:times;text-align:justify"><FONT SIZE=2>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;We
believe this policy should include any direct or indirect contribution that is intended to influence the outcome of an election or referendum. It should also prohibit the use of trade
associations or non-profit corporations from channeling our company's contributions or membership dues to influence the outcome of any election or referendum. </FONT></P>

<P style="font-family:times;text-align:justify"><FONT SIZE=2><B> Position of the Board of Directors  </B></FONT></P>

<P style="font-family:times;text-align:justify"><FONT SIZE=2>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;The Board of Directors has considered this proposal and believes that its adoption at this time is not in the best interests of Target
or our shareholders. </FONT></P>

<P style="font-family:times;text-align:justify"><FONT SIZE=2>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;The
Board acknowledges the importance of the issue of the role of corporations in public policy activities. Following our experience during the 2010 election cycle, the Board conducted a
comprehensive review of our policies and practices in this area, which led to the adoption of a clear and transparent framework for Target's public policy engagement based on:</FONT></P>

<UL>
<DL compact>
<DT style='font-family:times;margin-bottom:-11pt;'><FONT SIZE=2>&#149;</FONT></DT><DD style="font-family:times;text-align:justify"><FONT SIZE=2>Alignment of our business interests and public policy activities; </FONT></DD></DL>
</UL>
<P ALIGN="CENTER" style="font-family:times;"><FONT SIZE=2>58</FONT></P>

<HR NOSHADE>
<P style='font-family:times;page-break-before:always'></p>
<!-- ZEQ.=4,SEQ=64,EFW="2207783",CP="TARGET CORPORATION",DN="1",CHK=423746,FOLIO='58',FILE='DISK114:[12ZAC1.12ZAC43801]DY43801A.;14',USER='DBEMBEN',CD='27-APR-2012;04:12' -->
<A NAME="page_dy43801_1_59"> </A>
<UL>
<DL compact>
<DT style='font-family:times;margin-bottom:-11pt;'><FONT SIZE=2>&#149;</FONT></DT><DD style="font-family:times;text-align:justify"><FONT SIZE=2>A rigorous internal governance process, including Board oversight, that supports this alignment; and </FONT> <FONT SIZE=2>
<BR><BR></FONT></DD><DT style='font-family:times;margin-bottom:-11pt;'><FONT SIZE=2>&#149;</FONT></DT><DD style="font-family:times;text-align:justify"><FONT SIZE=2>Transparency to shareholders, guests, team members and other stakeholders. </FONT></DD></DL>
</UL>

<P style="font-family:times;text-align:justify"><FONT SIZE=2>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;During
the course of this review the Board considered whether to adopt a ban on the use of any corporate treasury funds for political purposes. It determined that a complete prohibition
of this nature was too absolute and could put Target at a disadvantage if there ever were circumstances when use of corporate funds would be in the best interests of the corporation. The Board
continues to believe that our framework for engagement, which combines a sound decision-making process, Board oversight and transparency to stakeholders, is the best approach. </FONT></P>

<P style="font-family:times;text-align:justify"><FONT SIZE=2>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;More
information about our public policy activities, including disclosure of individual contributions and a discussion of how we prohibit trade associations from using any of Target's
dues for political campaigns, can be found at: </FONT><FONT SIZE=2><I>hereforgood.target.com/learn-more/civic-activity</I></FONT><FONT SIZE=2>. </FONT></P>


<P style="font-family:times;text-align:justify"><FONT SIZE=2>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;</FONT><FONT
SIZE=2><B>THE BOARD OF DIRECTORS RECOMMENDS THAT SHAREHOLDERS VOTE "AGAINST" THE SHAREHOLDER PROPOSAL THAT WOULD PROHIBIT OUR USE OF CORPORATE FUNDS FOR ANY POLITICAL
ELECTION OR CAMPAIGN.  </B></FONT></P>

<P ALIGN="CENTER" style="font-family:times;"><FONT SIZE=2><B> <A NAME="dy43801_additional_information"> </A>
<A NAME="toc_dy43801_9"> </A>
<BR>  ADDITIONAL INFORMATION    <BR>    </B></FONT></P>

<P style="font-family:times;text-align:justify"><FONT SIZE=2><B> Business Ethics and Conduct  </B></FONT></P>

<P style="font-family:times;text-align:justify"><FONT SIZE=2>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;We are committed to conducting business lawfully and ethically. All of our directors and employees, including our Chief Executive
Officer and senior financial officers, are required to act at all times with honesty and integrity. Our Business Conduct Guide covers areas of professional conduct, including conflicts of interest,
the protection of corporate opportunities and assets, employment policies, confidentiality, vendor standards and intellectual property, and requires
strict adherence to all laws and regulations applicable to our business. Our Business Conduct Guide also describes the means by which any employee can provide an anonymous report of an actual or
apparent violation of our Business Conduct Guide. </FONT></P>

<P style="font-family:times;text-align:justify"><FONT SIZE=2>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;We
intend to disclose any future amendments to, or waivers from, any provision of our Business Conduct Guide involving our directors, our principal executive officer, principal financial
officer, principal accounting officer, controller or other persons performing similar functions on our website within four business days following the date of any such amendment or waiver. No waivers
were sought or granted in fiscal 2011. </FONT></P>

<P style="font-family:times;text-align:justify"><FONT SIZE=2><B> Vendor Standards and Compliance  </B></FONT></P>

<P style="font-family:times;text-align:justify"><FONT SIZE=2>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;To ensure that the products we carry in our stores are made legally and ethically, we require our vendors to abide by certain
standards. Copies of those standards and related materials are included at </FONT><FONT SIZE=2><I>hereforgood.target.com/learn-more/responsible-sourcing</I></FONT><FONT SIZE=2>. </FONT></P>


<P style="font-family:times;text-align:justify"><FONT SIZE=2><B> Commitment to Diversity  </B></FONT></P>

<P style="font-family:times;text-align:justify"><FONT SIZE=2>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;At the heart of our company are the diverse backgrounds and perspectives of our more than 365,000 Target team members. The diversity of
our team fosters a unique, inclusive culture that is collaborative, dynamic and guided by our shared commitment to delivering outstanding results. The market insight, community-building and commitment
of our African American, Asian American, Hispanic, GLBT, Women's and Military Business Councils help make Target a great place to work and inform business decisions that create a competitive
advantage. Our Vice President of Diversity&nbsp;&amp; Inclusion leads a team that works to integrate the Business Councils with our companywide diversity strategy. </FONT></P>

<P ALIGN="CENTER" style="font-family:times;"><FONT SIZE=2>59</FONT></P>

<HR NOSHADE>
<P style='font-family:times;page-break-before:always'></p>
<!-- ZEQ.=5,SEQ=65,EFW="2207783",CP="TARGET CORPORATION",DN="1",CHK=65095,FOLIO='59',FILE='DISK114:[12ZAC1.12ZAC43801]DY43801A.;14',USER='DBEMBEN',CD='27-APR-2012;04:12' -->
<A NAME="page_dy43801_1_60"> </A>

<P style="font-family:times;text-align:justify"><FONT SIZE=2>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;We
also believe it's important that our stores and merchandise reflect the communities in which we operate. As a result, we actively recruit and engage diverse suppliers and business
partners through meaningful participation in national and local organizations focused on diverse business development. In addition, we extend this commitment to our involvement in many innovative
programs, partnerships
and sponsorships that share our objective of fostering an inclusive culture. We care about the needs of the communities we serve, and embrace their diversity through our support. Information regarding
our diversity programs is located at </FONT><FONT SIZE=2><I>www.target.com/diversity.</I></FONT></P>

<P style="font-family:times;text-align:justify"><FONT SIZE=2>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;For
the benefit of hearing impaired persons, a sign language interpreter will be present at our 2012 Annual Meeting. </FONT></P>

<P style="font-family:times;text-align:justify"><FONT SIZE=2><B> Strengthening Communities  </B></FONT></P>

<P style="font-family:times;text-align:justify"><FONT SIZE=2>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;Since 1946, Target has donated 5&nbsp;percent of its income to improve the health and safety of the communities in which we operate.
Today, that commitment extends to more than 1,700 neighborhoods throughout the U.S. and nearly 30 countries around the world. Each week, we give on average more than $3&nbsp;million and numerous
volunteer hours to make a positive impact in the lives of our guests and team members. </FONT></P>

<P style="font-family:times;text-align:justify"><FONT SIZE=2>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;Target's
longstanding dedication to improving the communities where we operate is punctuated by several core commitments, including paving a path to graduation by supporting
K-12 education; reducing our environmental impact; inspiring our guests, team members and their families as they strive to achieve their well-being goals; and operating safe
stores that help our communities thrive. </FONT></P>

<P style="font-family:times;text-align:justify"><FONT SIZE=2>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;Our
legacy of community giving&#151;both in terms of financial support and team member volunteer hours&#151;is a hallmark of our brand and a differentiating factor in
Target's ability to attract and retain top talent. To learn more about Target's commitment to strengthening communities as a responsible corporate citizen, visit </FONT> <FONT SIZE=2><I>hereforgood.target.com</I></FONT><FONT SIZE=2>. </FONT></P>

<P ALIGN="CENTER" style="font-family:times;"><FONT SIZE=2><A
NAME="dy43801_shareholder_information"> </A>
<A NAME="toc_dy43801_10"> </A>
<BR></FONT><FONT SIZE=2><B>  SHAREHOLDER INFORMATION    <BR>    </B></FONT></P>


<P style="font-family:times;text-align:justify"><FONT SIZE=2><B> Shareholder Proposals  </B></FONT></P>

<P style="font-family:times;text-align:justify"><FONT SIZE=2>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;Proposals by shareholders (other than director nominations) that are submitted for inclusion in our proxy statement for our 2013 Annual
Meeting must follow the procedures set forth in Rule&nbsp;14a-8 under the Securities Exchange Act of 1934 and our bylaws. To be timely under Rule&nbsp;14a-8, they must be
received by our Corporate Secretary at Target Corporation, 1000 Nicollet Mall, Mail Stop TPS-2670, Minneapolis, Minnesota 55403 by December&nbsp;31, 2012. </FONT></P>

<P style="font-family:times;text-align:justify"><FONT SIZE=2>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;If
a shareholder does not submit a proposal for inclusion in our proxy statement but does wish to propose an item of business to be considered at the annual meeting of shareholders
(other than director nominations), that shareholder must give advance written notice of such proposal to our Corporate Secretary, which notice must be received at least 90&nbsp;days prior to the
anniversary of the most recent annual meeting. For our 2013 Annual Meeting, notice must be received by March&nbsp;15, 2013, and must comply with all applicable statutes and regulations, as well as
certain other provisions contained in our bylaws, which generally require the shareholder to provide a brief description of the proposed business, reasons for proposing the business and certain
information about the shareholder and the Target securities held by the shareholder. </FONT></P>

<P style="font-family:times;text-align:justify"><FONT SIZE=2>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;Under
our bylaws, if a shareholder plans to nominate a person as a director at an annual meeting, the shareholder is required to place the proposed director's name in nomination by
written request received by our Corporate Secretary at least 90&nbsp;days prior to the anniversary of the most recent annual meeting. Shareholder-proposed nominations for our 2013 Annual Meeting
must be received by March&nbsp;15, 2013, and must comply with all applicable statutes and regulations, as well as certain other provisions contained in </FONT></P>

<P ALIGN="CENTER" style="font-family:times;"><FONT SIZE=2>60</FONT></P>

<A NAME="page_dy43801_1_61"> </A>

<P style="font-family:times;text-align:justify"><FONT SIZE=2>our
bylaws, which generally require the shareholder to provide certain information about the proposed director, the shareholder and the Target securities held by the shareholder. </FONT></P>


<P style="font-family:times;text-align:justify"><FONT SIZE=2><B> Householding Information  </B></FONT></P>

<P style="font-family:times;text-align:justify"><FONT SIZE=2>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;We have adopted a procedure approved by the SEC called "householding." Under this procedure, certain shareholders of record who have
the same address and last name and do not participate in electronic delivery of proxy materials will receive only one copy of our annual report and proxy statement, unless one or more of these
shareholders notifies us that they would like to continue to receive individual copies. This will reduce our printing costs and postage fees. Shareholders who participate in householding will continue
to receive separate proxy cards. Also, householding will not in any way affect dividend check mailings. </FONT></P>


<P style="font-family:times;text-align:justify"><FONT SIZE=2>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;If
you and other shareholders of record with whom you share an address currently receive multiple copies of our annual report and/or proxy statement, or if you hold stock in more than
one account, and in either case, you would like to receive only a single copy of the annual report or proxy statement for your household, please contact our Investor Relations representative by email
at investorrelations@target.com, by mail to the address listed on the cover of this proxy statement, Attention: Investor Relations, or by telephone at (612)&nbsp;761-6736. </FONT></P>

<P style="font-family:times;text-align:justify"><FONT SIZE=2>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;If
you participate in householding and would like to receive a separate copy of our 2011 annual report or this proxy statement, please contact us in the manner described in the
immediately preceding paragraph. We will deliver the requested documents to you promptly upon receipt of your request. </FONT></P>

<P ALIGN="CENTER" style="font-family:times;"><FONT SIZE=2>61</FONT></P>

<P ALIGN="RIGHT" style="font-family:times;"><FONT SIZE=2><A
NAME="ha43801_appendix_a"> </A>
<A NAME="toc_ha43801_1"> </A>
<BR></FONT><FONT SIZE=2><B>  APPENDIX A    <BR>    </B></FONT></P>

<P ALIGN="CENTER" style="font-family:times;"><FONT SIZE=2><A
NAME="ha43801_t&#97;rget_corporation_officer_sho__tar02672"> </A>
<A NAME="toc_ha43801_2"> </A>
<BR></FONT><FONT SIZE=2><B>  TARGET CORPORATION<BR>  OFFICER SHORT-TERM INCENTIVE PLAN<BR>  </B></FONT><FONT SIZE=2>(Adopted on March&nbsp;14, 2012)    <BR></FONT></P>

<P ALIGN="CENTER" style="font-family:times;"><FONT SIZE=2><A
NAME="ha43801_article_i_#151;background"> </A>
<A NAME="toc_ha43801_3"> </A>
<BR></FONT><FONT SIZE=2><B>  Article&nbsp;I&#151;Background    <BR>    </B></FONT></P>

<P style="font-family:times;text-align:justify"><FONT SIZE=2><B>1.1&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;<U>Name</U>.</B></FONT><FONT SIZE=2>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;The name of this plan is the "Target Corporation Officer Short-Term
Incentive Plan." It is sometimes hereinafter referred to as the "STIP" or the "Plan." Unless otherwise defined in the Plan or the context clearly indicates to the contrary, capitalized terms are
defined in Article&nbsp;II. </FONT></P>

<P style="font-family:times;text-align:justify"><FONT SIZE=2><B>1.2&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;<U>Compensation Policy and Plan Intent</U>.</B></FONT><FONT SIZE=2>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;The Plan is intended to promote the Company's
pay-for-performance compensation philosophy by providing incentive cash bonus payments to designated upper-level executives, who through their efforts directly and
significantly impact the achievement of Company goals and objectives. </FONT></P>

<P style="font-family:times;text-align:justify"><FONT SIZE=2><B>1.3&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;<U>Eligibility</U>.</B></FONT><FONT SIZE=2>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;Bonuses may be granted to any Executive Officer who is designated as a
Participant from time to time by the Committee or any other officer who is designated as a Participant from time to time by the Chief Executive Officer of the Company. Designation as a Participant for
a Bonus in one period shall not confer on a Participant the right to participate in the Plan for any other period. </FONT></P>

<P ALIGN="CENTER" style="font-family:times;"><FONT SIZE=2><A
NAME="ha43801_article_ii_#151;definitions"> </A>
<A NAME="toc_ha43801_4"> </A>
<BR></FONT><FONT SIZE=2><B>  Article&nbsp;II&#151;Definitions    <BR>    </B></FONT></P>

<P style="font-family:times;text-align:justify"><FONT SIZE=2><B>2.1&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;<U>Board</U>.</B></FONT><FONT SIZE=2>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;"Board" means the Board of Directors of the Company. </FONT></P>

<P style="font-family:times;text-align:justify"><FONT SIZE=2><B>2.2&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;<U>Bonus</U>.</B></FONT><FONT SIZE=2>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;"Bonus" means an incentive award which, subject to such terms and conditions as may
be prescribed by the Committee, entitles a Participant to receive a cash bonus payment from the Company pursuant to Article&nbsp;III. </FONT></P>

<P style="font-family:times;text-align:justify"><FONT SIZE=2><B>2.3&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;<U>Code</U>.</B></FONT><FONT SIZE=2>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;"Code" refers to the Internal Revenue Code of 1986, as amended. </FONT></P>


<P style="font-family:times;text-align:justify"><FONT SIZE=2><B>2.4&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;<U>Company</U>.</B></FONT><FONT SIZE=2>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;"Company" refers to Target Corporation and its subsidiaries. </FONT></P>

<P style="font-family:times;text-align:justify"><FONT SIZE=2><B>2.5&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;<U>Committee</U>.</B></FONT><FONT SIZE=2>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;"Committee" means the Compensation Committee of the Board and if no such named
committee shall be designated by the Board, it shall mean the Committee of the Board most nearly performing the duties of the Compensation Committee as defined at the time of its elimination as a
Board Committee. </FONT></P>

<P style="font-family:times;text-align:justify"><FONT SIZE=2><B>2.6&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;<U>Covered Officer</U>.</B></FONT><FONT SIZE=2>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;"Covered Officer" includes all Participants whose compensation, in the
Performance Period for which the Bonus is calculated, is or, in the Committee's discretion, may be subject to the compensation expense deduction limitations set forth in Section&nbsp;162(m) of the
Code. </FONT></P>

<P style="font-family:times;text-align:justify"><FONT SIZE=2><B>2.7&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;<U>Determination Date</U>.</B></FONT><FONT SIZE=2>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;"Determination Date" means the latest possible date that will not
jeopardize a Bonus' qualification as Performance-Based Compensation. </FONT></P>

<P style="font-family:times;text-align:justify"><FONT SIZE=2><B>2.8&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;<U>Executive Officer</U>.</B></FONT><FONT SIZE=2>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;"Executive Officer" is as defined in Rule&nbsp;3b-7 under
the Securities Exchange Act of 1934, as amended. </FONT></P>

<P style="font-family:times;text-align:justify"><FONT SIZE=2><B>2.9&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;<U>Participants</U>.</B></FONT><FONT SIZE=2>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;"Participants" mean executives participating in the Plan, pursuant to
Section&nbsp;1.3. </FONT></P>

<P ALIGN="CENTER" style="font-family:times;"><FONT SIZE=2>A-1</FONT></P>

<HR NOSHADE>
<P style='font-family:times;page-break-before:always'></p>
<!-- ZEQ.=1,SEQ=68,EFW="2207783",CP="TARGET CORPORATION",DN="1",CHK=820039,FOLIO='A-1',FILE='DISK114:[12ZAC1.12ZAC43801]HA43801A.;14',USER='DBEMBEN',CD='27-APR-2012;04:12' -->
<A NAME="page_ha43801_1_2"> </A>

<P style="font-family:times;text-align:justify"><FONT SIZE=2><B>2.10&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;<U>Performance-Based Compensation</U>.</B></FONT><FONT SIZE=2>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;"Performance-Based Compensation" means a Bonus that is
intended to constitute "performance-based compensation" within the meaning of Section&nbsp;162(m)(4)(C) of the Code and the regulations promulgated thereunder. </FONT></P>


<P style="font-family:times;text-align:justify"><FONT SIZE=2><B>2.11&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;<U>Performance Measures</U>.</B></FONT><FONT SIZE=2>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;"Performance Measures" mean one or a combination of two or more of the
following performance-based metrics, as approved by the Committee; provided, however, that different Performance Measures may be approved for different Participants during the same Performance Period:
revenues; sales; comparable store sales; earnings before interest and taxes; earnings before interest, taxes, depreciation and amortization; earnings before taxes; net earnings; earnings per share;
economic value added; total shareholder return; and credit card spread to LIBOR. In addition, for any Bonus to a Participant that is not intended to constitute Performance-Based Compensation,
Performance Measures may include, alone or in combination with the foregoing Performance Measures, any other measure of performance as determined by the Committee. </FONT></P>


<P style="font-family:times;text-align:justify"><FONT SIZE=2><B>2.12&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;<U>Performance Period</U>.</B></FONT><FONT SIZE=2>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;"Performance Period" is the period, which shall not exceed four
consecutive fiscal quarters, specified by the Committee at the time a Bonus is granted. </FONT></P>

<P ALIGN="CENTER" style="font-family:times;"><FONT SIZE=2><A
NAME="ha43801_article_iii_#151;bonuses"> </A>
<A NAME="toc_ha43801_5"> </A>
<BR></FONT><FONT SIZE=2><B>  Article&nbsp;III&#151;Bonuses    <BR>    </B></FONT></P>

<P style="font-family:times;text-align:justify"><FONT SIZE=2><B>3.1&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;<U>General</U>.</B></FONT><FONT SIZE=2>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;Bonuses may be granted to a Participant in such amounts and upon such terms, and at
any time and from time to time, as shall be determined by the Committee. The Committee, at the time a Bonus is made, shall specify the terms and conditions which govern the Bonus, which terms and
conditions may prescribe (or, in the case of Bonuses intended to constitute Performance-Based Compensation, shall prescribe) the degree of attainment of such Performance Measures required for payment
of a Bonus and that the Bonus shall be earned only upon, and to the extent that, Performance Measures as described in Section&nbsp;3.2 are satisfied within the Performance Period for the Bonus. The
Committee may establish terms and conditions for payment of Bonuses in the event of changes of duties of any Participant with the Company or any subsidiary of the Company during the Performance Period
or in the event of a Participant's termination of employment (including death, disability, retirement, or termination with or without cause) or leave of absence. Different terms and conditions may be
established by the Committee for different Bonuses and for different Participants. </FONT></P>

<P style="font-family:times;text-align:justify"><FONT SIZE=2><B>3.2&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;<U>Performance Measures</U>.</B></FONT><FONT SIZE=2>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;Payment of Bonuses shall be contingent upon the degree of attainment of
such Performance Measures over the Performance Period. With respect to each Performance Period, Performance Measures will be established and approved by the Committee on or before the Determination
Date. Multiple Performance Periods may be established, each with different lengths and which run concurrently. Performance Measures may be absolute in their terms, on a per share basis, measured as a
change from prior periods or measured against or in relationship to other companies comparably, similarly or otherwise situated. Each measure that is a financial measure shall be adjusted if so
determined by the Committee, to exclude the effects of extraordinary items, unusual or non-recurring events, changes in accounting principles or methods, realized investment gains or
losses, discontinued operations, acquisitions, divestitures, material restructuring or impairment charges, retained and uninsured losses for natural catastrophes and any other items as the Committee
determines to be required so that the operating results of the Company, segment, subsidiary, operating company, division, unit or test strategy or new venture, as applicable, shall be computed on a
basis consistent with the Performance Measures established for the Performance Period; provided that no such adjustment shall be made if the effect of such adjustment would be to cause the related
Performance-Based Compensation to fail to qualify as Performance-Based Compensation. The Committee may in its discretion classify Participants into as many groups as it determines, and as to any
Participant relate his/her Performance Measures partially, or entirely, to the measured performance, either absolutely or relatively, of an identified segment, subsidiary, operating company, division,
unit or test strategy, new venture of the Company or individual performance. </FONT></P>

<P ALIGN="CENTER" style="font-family:times;"><FONT SIZE=2>A-2</FONT></P>

<HR NOSHADE>
<P style='font-family:times;page-break-before:always'></p>
<!-- ZEQ.=2,SEQ=69,EFW="2207783",CP="TARGET CORPORATION",DN="1",CHK=947047,FOLIO='A-2',FILE='DISK114:[12ZAC1.12ZAC43801]HA43801A.;14',USER='DBEMBEN',CD='27-APR-2012;04:12' -->
<A NAME="page_ha43801_1_3"> </A>

<P style="font-family:times;text-align:justify"><FONT SIZE=2><B>3.3&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;<U>Payment of Bonuses</U>.</B></FONT><FONT SIZE=2>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;Following the completion of each Performance Period, the Committee shall
certify the level of attainment of the applicable Performance Measures for each Executive Officer. Bonuses shall be paid to Participants in cash at a time determined by the Committee, but in no event
later than two and one-half months after the end of the fiscal year in which the Performance Period ends. However, any Participant who is a participant in a deferred compensation plan may
defer payment of his/her Bonus if and to the extent permissible under any such plan. In no event shall a Covered Officer receive a Bonus in any fiscal year that exceeds the lesser of
(i)&nbsp;$7,000,000 or (ii)&nbsp;400% of the Covered Officer's base salary (prior to any salary reduction or deferral elections) as of the date of grant of the Bonus. </FONT></P>

<P style="font-family:times;text-align:justify"><FONT SIZE=2><B>3.4&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;<U>Adjustments</U>.</B></FONT><FONT SIZE=2>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;The Committee is authorized at any time during or after a Performance Period, in
its sole and absolute discretion, to reduce or eliminate a Bonus payable to any Participant for any reason. No reduction in a Bonus payable to any Participant shall increase the amount of the Bonus
payable to any other Participant. </FONT></P>

<P ALIGN="CENTER" style="font-family:times;"><FONT SIZE=2><A
NAME="ha43801_article_iv_#151;general"> </A>
<A NAME="toc_ha43801_6"> </A>
<BR></FONT><FONT SIZE=2><B>  Article&nbsp;IV&#151;General    <BR>    </B></FONT></P>

<P style="font-family:times;text-align:justify"><FONT SIZE=2><B>4.1&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;<U>Beneficiary</U>.</B></FONT><FONT SIZE=2>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;Any Bonus which becomes distributable after the death of a Participant shall be
paid as it becomes due to such person or persons, or other legal entity as the Participant may have designated in writing delivered to the Company's or his/her division's personnel office on an
approved form. The Participant may, from time to time, revoke or change any such designation by writing delivered to such personnel office on an approved form. If there is no unrevoked designation on
file with such personnel office at the Participant's death, or if the person or persons designated therein shall have all predeceased the Participant, such payments shall be made to the Participant's
estate. If a Participant has deferred his/her Bonus pursuant to a plan or arrangement with the Company, the plan or arrangement shall govern the beneficiary designation. </FONT></P>

<P style="font-family:times;text-align:justify"><FONT SIZE=2><B>4.2&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;<U>Administration and Interpretation of Plan</U>.</B></FONT><FONT SIZE=2>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;This Plan shall be interpreted by the Committee
and its interpretations shall be final and binding on Participants and all other parties in interest. </FONT></P>

<P style="font-family:times;text-align:justify"><FONT SIZE=2>The
Plan shall be administered by the Committee. The Committee reserves the right, from time to time, to prescribe rules and regulations which are not inconsistent with the provisions of the Plan, and
to modify or revoke such rules and regulations at such time and in such manner as it may deem proper. The Committee may, on or before the Determination Date, specify a pool from which some or all
Bonuses may be paid to all Participants in accordance with this Plan and grant Bonuses under Section&nbsp;3.1 based on allocations from such pool. A copy of the then current Plan shall be maintained
in the Company's personnel office and shall be available, upon request, for review by any Participant or
his duly authorized agent. The Committee may correct any defect, supply any omission or reconcile any inconsistency in this Plan or in any Bonus in the manner and to the extent it shall deem
desirable. The determinations of the Committee in the administration of this Plan, as described herein, shall be final, binding and conclusive, subject to the provisions of this Plan. A majority of
the members of the Committee shall constitute a quorum for any meeting of the Committee. </FONT></P>

<P style="font-family:times;text-align:justify"><FONT SIZE=2>All
persons in the Plan shall be bound by the terms of the Plan and of all rules and regulations pursuant thereto, all as now in effect or hereafter amended, promulgated or passed which shall likewise
be maintained at the Company's personnel office. </FONT></P>

<P style="font-family:times;text-align:justify"><FONT SIZE=2><B>4.3&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;<U>Rights of Participants and Beneficiaries</U>.</B></FONT><FONT SIZE=2>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;The Plan is not an employment agreement and does
not ensure or evidence to any degree the continued employment or the claim to continued employment of any Participant for any time or period or job. </FONT></P>

<P ALIGN="CENTER" style="font-family:times;"><FONT SIZE=2>A-3</FONT></P>

<HR NOSHADE>
<P style='font-family:times;page-break-before:always'></p>
<!-- ZEQ.=3,SEQ=70,EFW="2207783",CP="TARGET CORPORATION",DN="1",CHK=856632,FOLIO='A-3',FILE='DISK114:[12ZAC1.12ZAC43801]HA43801A.;14',USER='DBEMBEN',CD='27-APR-2012;04:12' -->
<A NAME="page_ha43801_1_4"> </A>


<P style="font-family:times;text-align:justify"><FONT SIZE=2>No
Participant or beneficiary shall, by virtue of this Plan, have any interest in any specific asset or assets of the Company. If a Bonus has been granted, a Participant or beneficiary has only an
unsecured contract right to receive cash payments in accordance with and at the times specified by the Plan. </FONT></P>

<P style="font-family:times;text-align:justify"><FONT SIZE=2>No
Participant shall have the right or ability to assign, pledge, or otherwise dispose of any part of a Bonus hereunder. </FONT></P>

<P style="font-family:times;text-align:justify"><FONT SIZE=2><B>4.4&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;<U>Authority of Chief Executive Officer</U>.</B></FONT><FONT SIZE=2>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;With respect to Participants who are not Executive
Officers, the Chief Executive Officer of the Company may exercise the authority of the Committee under this Plan, except (a)&nbsp;to the extent the Committee chooses to exercise such authority, or
(b)&nbsp;where such authority must be exercised by the Committee under Section&nbsp;162(m) of the Code, or (c)&nbsp;unless otherwise delegated by the Board or the Committee, where such authority
involves amending or modifying the Plan pursuant to Section&nbsp;4.5. </FONT></P>

<P style="font-family:times;text-align:justify"><FONT SIZE=2><B>4.5&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;<U>Amendment, Modification and Termination of the Plan</U>.</B></FONT><FONT SIZE=2>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;The Committee may at any time terminate,
suspend or modify the Plan and the terms and provisions of any Bonus to any Participant which has not been paid. Amendments are subject to approval of the shareholders of the Company only if such
approval is necessary to maintain the Plan in compliance with the requirements of Section&nbsp;162(m) of the Code, its successor provisions or any other applicable law or regulation. No Bonus may be
granted during any suspension of the Plan or after its termination. </FONT></P>

<P style="font-family:times;text-align:justify"><FONT SIZE=2><B>4.6&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;<U>Unfunded Plan</U>.</B></FONT><FONT SIZE=2>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;The Plan shall be unfunded, and the Company shall not be required to segregate
any assets that may at any time be represented by Bonuses under the Plan. </FONT></P>

<P style="font-family:times;text-align:justify"><FONT SIZE=2><B>4.7&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;<U>Other Benefit and Compensation Programs</U>.</B></FONT><FONT SIZE=2>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;Neither the adoption of the Plan by the Committee
nor its submission to the shareholders of the Company shall be construed as creating any limitation on the power of the Board to adopt such other incentive arrangements as it may deem appropriate. </FONT></P>

<P style="font-family:times;text-align:justify"><FONT SIZE=2><B>4.8&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;<U>Governing Law</U>.</B></FONT><FONT SIZE=2>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;To the extent that federal laws do not otherwise control, the Plan and all
determinations made and actions taken pursuant to the Plan shall be governed by the laws of the State of Minnesota without regard to its conflicts-of-law principles and shall
be construed accordingly. The exclusive forum and venue for any legal action arising out of or related to the Plan shall be the United States District Court for the District of Minnesota, and each
Participant, as a condition of participating in the Plan, submits to the personal jurisdiction of that court. If neither subject matter nor diversity jurisdiction exists in the United States District
Court for the District of Minnesota, then the exclusive forum and venue for any such action shall be the courts of the State of Minnesota located in Hennepin County, and each Participant, as a
condition of participating in the Plan, submits to the personal jurisdiction of that court. </FONT></P>

<P style="font-family:times;text-align:justify"><FONT SIZE=2><B>4.9&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;<U>Tax Withholding</U>.</B></FONT><FONT SIZE=2>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;The Company shall have the right to withhold from cash payments under the
Plan to a Participant or other person an amount sufficient to cover any withholding taxes the Company reasonably determines are legally payable by the Participant. </FONT></P>

<P style="font-family:times;text-align:justify"><FONT SIZE=2><B>4.10&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;<U>Compensation Recoupment Policy</U>.</B></FONT><FONT SIZE=2>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;Bonuses may be made subject to any compensation recoupment
policy adopted by the Board or the Committee at any time prior to or after the effective date of the Plan, and as such policy may be amended from time to time after its adoption. </FONT></P>

<P style="font-family:times;text-align:justify"><FONT SIZE=2><B>4.11&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;<U>Miscellaneous Provisions</U>.</B></FONT></P>

<P style="font-family:times;text-align:justify"><FONT SIZE=2>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;a.&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;<U>Headings</U>.&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;Headings
at the beginning of sections hereof are for convenience of reference, shall not be considered a part of the
text of the Plan, and shall not influence its construction. </FONT></P>

<P ALIGN="CENTER" style="font-family:times;"><FONT SIZE=2>A-4</FONT></P>

<HR NOSHADE>
<P style='font-family:times;page-break-before:always'></p>
<!-- ZEQ.=4,SEQ=71,EFW="2207783",CP="TARGET CORPORATION",DN="1",CHK=774754,FOLIO='A-4',FILE='DISK114:[12ZAC1.12ZAC43801]HA43801A.;14',USER='DBEMBEN',CD='27-APR-2012;04:12' -->
<A NAME="page_ha43801_1_5"> </A>

<P style="font-family:times;text-align:justify"><FONT SIZE=2>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;b.&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;<U>Construed
as a Whole</U>.&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;The provisions of the Plan shall be construed as a whole in such manner as to carry out the provisions
thereof and shall not be construed separately without relation to the context. </FONT></P>

<P style="font-family:times;text-align:justify"><FONT SIZE=2><B>4.12&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;<U>Effective Date of the Plan</U>.</B></FONT><FONT SIZE=2>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;The Plan shall become effective as of February&nbsp;3, 2013;
provided that this Plan is approved and ratified by the shareholders of the Company no later than June&nbsp;30, 2012. The Plan shall remain in effect until it has been terminated pursuant to
Section&nbsp;4.5. </FONT></P>

<P ALIGN="CENTER" style="font-family:times;"><FONT SIZE=2>A-5</FONT></P>

  the proportionate interest in shares held by the Target Common Stock Fund

  in the same proportion as instructions actually received by the Trustee from
  Plan participants who gave voting instructions. Instruction forms received by
